    {
      "id": "b8db6e9837bff8cd769b69b173cde4796ff7996a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 337,
        "name": "Li Xi",
        "email": "lixi@ddn.com",
        "username": "LiX"
      },
      "date": "2018-11-02 15:09:07.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nSome Lustre related codes are put into Ext4 patch. These codes should be moved to OSD level.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "593efcc4228210c6acddf76073deed61803c13a6",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 337,
        "name": "Li Xi",
        "email": "lixi@ddn.com",
        "username": "LiX"
      },
      "date": "2018-11-02 15:25:29.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nThe global snap_lock_list in Ext4 patch seems not efficient. All inodes share the same list. If snapshots of a lot of inodes are being accessed, there will be severe lock contention.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "998aee028556d7314d03d3d775dfea6b08edd9ef",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 337,
        "name": "Li Xi",
        "email": "lixi@ddn.com",
        "username": "LiX"
      },
      "date": "2018-11-02 15:30:59.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nThe snapshot inodes for a origin file are being connected together by extended attributes of the inodes. The extended attributes uses the inode numbers to point to inodes. I feel at least, the extended attribute EXT4_XATTR_NAME_SNAPSHOT_LINK can be moved into internal fields of an inode.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "27430035f1fffd0587eadd6ebe38ac22700cf2a4",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 428,
        "name": "Wang Shilong",
        "email": "wangshilong1991@gmail.com",
        "username": "wangshilong",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2018-11-02 23:31:54.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nbtw, original goal of this patch tries to add support without modifications to Ext4 disk format.\n\nUse internal fields of an inode might be more efficient, but it will break disk format unless\nupstream accept the patch or at least reseve some space for this usage.\n\nFYI, many years ago, some guys try to add some snapshot codes to ext4, but finally, community\ndecided No for this..",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
